  "report": {
    "narrative": [
      "Current capacity pressure is dominated by scheduler queue backlog in two Slurm partitions: mi3001x (36 pending) and mi2104x (26 pending). Of these, mi3001x is the top priority because it combines the largest backlog with elevated CPU saturation (0.75), indicating a likely user-visible throughput bottleneck (insufficient available nodes/GPUs, constraints, or policy limits). mi2104x shows the second-largest backlog with moderate saturation (~0.62), suggesting either partial capacity limits or scheduling constraints rather than absolute saturation.\n\nSeveral other partitions are fully CPU-saturated (mi3008x, mi3258x, mi3508x at 1.0) but have very small pending queues (1–2). Operationally, these look “hot but flowing” (busy resources with little waiting), so they are lower priority unless saturation persists alongside rising pending counts or increased job runtimes.\n\nHost-level hotspots from the inventory snapshot show two urgent outliers: chi-gpu-001 (training-a) is degraded with extreme CPU load (0.92) and memory pressure (0.88), making it the highest immediate host risk for performance degradation or OOM/thrashing. dal-storage-017 (analytics-b) is warning with high memory pressure (0.79) and the highest disk pressure (0.73), raising risk of I/O latency, throttling, or storage service impact.\n\nThermal pressure is also present on GPUs: top temperatures reach 82°C and 81°C on k002-004-* (card 0). If these temperatures are sustained (not transient spikes), they can trigger throttling and increase failure rates; prioritize inspection if your thermal guardrails are ~80°C+.\n\nOperator prioritization order: (1) mi3001x backlog + saturation (confirm down/drained nodes, reservation/QOS/accounting constraints, and whether demand warrants policy adjustments or capacity rebalancing), (2) mi2104x backlog (same checks, plus whether constraints are driving queuing), (3) chi-gpu-001 degraded compute contention (top processes/jobs, OOM logs, swap, cgroup limits, hardware health), (4) dal-storage-017 disk+memory pressure (disk utilization/latency/IOPS, SMART/RAID, filesystem errors, top talkers), (5) hot GPU nodes k002-004-* (cooling/airflow/fan telemetry; verify sustained temps under load).\n\nCoverage caveat: the inventory snapshot shown is only 4 hosts, while VictoriaMetrics reports 72 instrumented hosts; treat host-level conclusions as indicative and re-run/expand host queries if you suspect additional hotspots outside the sample."
    ],
    "highlights": [
      "Highest queue pressure: mi3001x with 36 pending and CPU saturation 0.75 → primary user-impact bottleneck to investigate first.",
      "Second queue hotspot: mi2104x with 26 pending and CPU saturation ~0.62 → likely constraint/capacity-limited; investigate after mi3001x.",
      "Saturated-but-low-queue partitions: mi3008x/mi3258x/mi3508x at 1.0 saturation with only 1–2 pending → lower priority unless pending trends up.",
      "Top host compute contention: chi-gpu-001 (training-a) CPU 0.92, mem 0.88, status=degraded → immediate triage for noisy neighbor/OOM/thrashing/hardware.",
      "Top storage risk: dal-storage-017 (analytics-b) mem 0.79, disk 0.73, status=warning → check disk latency/utilization and storage health.",
      "GPU thermals: k002-004-* card0 up to 82°C → investigate if sustained (throttling/failure risk)."
